\[
\text{Cups per cookie} = \frac{8 \text{ cups}}{12 \text{ cookies}} = \frac{2}{3} \text{ cups per cookie}
\]

Next, we use the cups per cookie to find out how many cups are needed for \(15\) cookies. We multiply the cups per cookie by the number of cookies:

\[
\text{Cups for 15 cookies} = \left(\frac{2}{3} \text{ cups per cookie}\right) \times 15 \text{ cookies} = \frac{2 \times 15}{3} = \frac{30}{3} = 10 \text{ cups}
\]

Thus, it will take \(10\) cups of chocolate chips to make \(15\) cookies. We write the final answer as:

\boxed{10}

